TIL: @scope lets you define where styles START applying and where they STOP. It's CSS containment boundaries.

@scope (.card) to (.card-footer) means "style everything inside .card but NOT inside .card-footer." The styles literally have a ceiling.

This is what Shadow DOM tried to solve but with the ergonomics of regular CSS. No JavaScript, no custom elements, just scoped styles.

code:
@scope (.card) to (.card-footer) {
  /* These styles apply inside .card
     but stop at .card-footer */
  p {
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  a {
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }
}

/* The footer has its own scope */
@scope (.card-footer) {
  a {
    color: var(--color-muted);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }
}

p {
  margin-top: 20px;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

